\begin_deeper
\begin_layout FrameSubtitle
This lecture borrows heavily from Nathan Hendren's notes.
 A big thank you to him.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Often ask 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

What government policies do the most to improve citizens' welfare?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Which policies should the government use to achieve a policy goal?
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Should high earners face a higher marginal income tax rate?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How can we reduce child poverty?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How much access should informal workers have to social insurance programs?
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Want to be able to leverage ever-increasing supply of estimates of causal
 impacts of a wide range of policy changes
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Credibility Revolution
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Angrist & Pischke, 2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
See also 2010 JEP (vol 24 issue 3) symposium on theory in development economics
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So how can we take all these causal estimates and translate them into statements
 about 
\emph on
desirability
\emph default
 of policy changes?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Need coherent framework to move from 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Positive
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Normative
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 analysis
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Welfare Concepts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Welfare
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Goal: What is the welfare impact of government policy changes?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Environment:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Government chooses a vector of policies 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 that can affect constraints and preferences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals maximize utility s.t.
 budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 indirect utility 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}\left(P\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
v_{i}\left(P\right)=\max_{x\in B_{i}\left(P\right)}u_{i}\left(x;P\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Very general: Admits households & firms, GE, discrete choices, heterogeneity
 etc.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Think about how this environment can incorporate
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Public goods expenditures?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Taxes?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Uncertainty and dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u_{i}=\textsf{E}\left[\sum_{t\geq0}\beta^{t}v_{it}\right]\right)$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Externalities?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Social Welfare
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define social welfare function (Bergson-Samuelson SWF)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(P\right)=\int_{i}{\color{red}\psi_{i}}v_{i}\left(P\right)di
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\color red
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset


\color inherit
 is individual 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's 
\series bold
Pareto weight
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}$
\end_inset

 can be a function (Saez & Stantcheva, 2016).
 What can it depend on?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Nests special (classic) case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(P\right)=\int_{i}\omega\left(v_{i}\right)di
\]

\end_inset

by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{i}=\omega^{\prime}\left(v_{i}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This will work well for small policy changes.
 What can happen when the changes are large? (more on this later).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Social Preferences
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define each individual's 
\series bold
social marginal utility of income 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula ${\color{green}\eta_{i}}={\color{red}\psi_{i}}{\color{blue}\lambda_{i}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{blue}\lambda_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
individual's
\emph default
 marginal utility of income.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\color{blue}\lambda_{i}}=\frac{d}{dy_{i}}v_{i}=\frac{\partial u_{i}}{\partial c}\;\text{(why?)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The ratio of two individuals' 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

s: 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}/\eta_{j}$
\end_inset

 corresponds to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Okun's Bucket
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Okun, 1976)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{i}/\eta_{j}=2$
\end_inset

 it means we are willing to take $1 from 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 to give $0.50 to 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These social marginal utilities of income provide general representations
 of social preferences
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What has been ruled out?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Impacts of Policy Changes on Social Welfare
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $W\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

 gives us a measure we can use to evaluate government policy changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a (small) policy change 
\begin_inset Formula $dp$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 an increase in a tax rate, a change in an eligibility threshold etc)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first-order effect of this on welfare is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dW}{dp}=\int_{i}{\color{red}\psi_{i}}\frac{dv_{i}}{dp}=\int_{i}{\color{green}\eta_{i}}\underbrace{\frac{dv_{i}/dp}{{\color{blue}\lambda_{i}}}}_{i\text{'s WTP}}={\color{green}\bar{\eta}_{p}}\int_{i}WTP_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{i}WTP_{i}=\int_{i}\tfrac{dv_{i}}{dp}/{\color{blue}\lambda_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the sum of WTP of affected individuals out of their own income for the
 policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{green}\bar{\eta}_{p}}=\int{\color{green}\eta_{i}}\frac{WTP_{i}}{\int_{i}WTP_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the incidence-weighted average social marginal utility of income 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Government's Budget Constraint
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Most policies (the 
\begin_inset Formula $dp$
\end_inset

) are not budget neutral, so we need to think about where the money comes
 from / goes
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
e.g.
 increased tax rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
expanded eligibility for transfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
audits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
switching from in-kind to cash transfers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Usually in empirical work we don't need to specify how to satisfy the government
's BC in order to achieve identification.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
But this implies that the counterfactual used for identification is generally
 not feasible
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The Government's Budget Constraint
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Envelope theorem: behavioral changes don't have 1st-order effects on individual
 welfare.
 Only mechanical effects.
 But behavioral changes do have effect on government's budget – the 
\emph on
Fiscal Externality.

\emph default
 How we account for these is at the heart of how we think about welfare
 effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
CBA + MCPF (Atkinson & Stern 1974; Kaplow 2011): Estimate Cost-Benefit ratio
 and adjust for DWL of taxation.
 Imagine closing budget by increasing linear tax rate (e.g.
 Heckman et al 2010)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
MEB/MDWL (Auerbach & Hines 2002 handbook).
 Imagine that we can use individual-specific transfers to close budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
MVPF (Mayshar 1990, Slemrod & Yitzhaki 1996, Hendren 2016, 2019): Imagine
 the budget is closed with some other policy (that you know the MVPF of).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slemrod & Yitzhaki (1996)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Antecedent to Hendren MVPF.
 Itself builds on Mayshar (1990)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Incorporates compliance and administrative costs (more on this in a few
 weeks)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Setup: Representative taxpayer with utility 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(X\right)$
\end_inset

 and budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $y=\sum_{i}q_{i}X_{i}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}=p_{i}+t_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\series bold
Marginal Burden
\series default
 of a tax reform 
\begin_inset Formula $dq_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MB=\sum_{i}X_{i}dq_{i}
\]

\end_inset

the income equivalent of the effects of the reform.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thank you Roy's identity (envelope theorem!) again.
 (WTP?)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slemrod & Yitzhaki (1996)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Tax revenue in this economy is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\left(t,p,y\right)=\sum_{i}t_{i}X_{i}\left(p+t,y\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For reform to be revenue neutral we require
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MR=\sum_{i}\frac{\partial R}{\partial t_{i}}dt_{i}=\sum_{i}MR_{i}dt_{i}=0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $MR_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\emph on
total
\emph default
 change in tax revenue due to changing 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Denoting the revenue effects 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{i}=MR_{i}dt_{i}$
\end_inset

 we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MB=\sum_{i}\frac{X_{i}}{MR_{i}}\delta_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where revenue neutrality requires 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\delta_{i}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slemrod & Yitzhaki (1996)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The object 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}/MR_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
Marginal Efficiency Cost of Public Funds 
\series default
(MECF).
 It's the cost to society of increasing tax revenue by a dollar through
 a change in the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th tax rate.
 It's the taxpayer's willingness to pay to avoid 
\begin_inset Formula $dt_{i}$
\end_inset

 over the effect of the reform on the goverment's budget.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example: Revenue-neutral tax reform involving two taxes: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}=-\delta_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MB=\left[\frac{X_{1}}{MR_{1}}\delta_{1}+\frac{X_{2}}{MR_{2}}\delta_{2}\right]=\left(MECF_{1}-MECF_{2}\right)\delta_{1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Now we can see what types of reforms increase welfare:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $MECF_{2}>MECF_{1}$
\end_inset

 then you want 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 (shift towards 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
if 
\begin_inset Formula $MECF_{2}<MECF_{1}$
\end_inset

 then you want 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}<0$
\end_inset

 (shift towards 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note that to implement this you only need 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1},X_{2}$
\end_inset

 (expenditures on the two goods) and 
\begin_inset Formula $MR_{1},MR_{2}$
\end_inset

 the marginal change in tax revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This can be applied to any part of the tax/transfer system, not just rates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slemrod & Yitzhaki (1996)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now incorporate avoidance/evasion, compliance costs and administrative costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The tax base for 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}$
\end_inset

, but that's not what is collected if we marginally increase 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

, we only collect 
\begin_inset Formula $MR_{1}$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{i}=\underbrace{\left(X_{i}-MR_{i}\right)}_{\text{leakage}}+MR_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What is the social value of these leaked dollars? 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Depends on what the taxpayer is willing to give up to avoid paying that
 dollar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bounded from above by $1.
 If it's avoidance, you'd pay up to a dollar to avoid that tax.
 If it's evasion, you'd bear up to $1 of increased risk to evade.
 Doesn't really matter what the mechanism is, just the willingness to pay.
 Call the marginal cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Slemrod & Yitzhaki (1996)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now add in marginal compliance costs to the taxpayer of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 and marginal administrative costs to the government of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MECF_{i}=\frac{\gamma\left(X_{i}-MR_{i}\right)+C_{i}+MR_{i}}{MR_{i}-A_{i}}=\frac{WTP}{\text{Effect on govt budget}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can also add in distributional concerns.
 Now we want to weight the burdens on the taxpayers 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 by their social marginal utility of income:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MECF_{i}=\frac{\frac{\sum_{h}\eta_{h}x_{ih}}{\sum_{h}\eta_{h}}}{MR_{i}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These concepts re-cast and shown to be empirically valuable in Hendren (2016)
 ad Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
But with a different name, the 
\series bold
Marginal Value of Public Funds (MVPF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Write the government budget in very general terms
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R\left(P\right)=g\left(P\right)-\int_{i}T\left(y_{i};P\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(P\right)$
\end_inset

 is government spending
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(\cdot;P\right)$
\end_inset

 is the tax schedule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 are taxable earnings
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $G=dR/dP$
\end_inset

: the marginal impact of the policy change on the government budget
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G=\frac{dg}{dp}-\int_{i}\left(\frac{\partial T}{\partial y_{i}}\frac{dy_{i}}{dp}+\frac{\partial T}{\partial p}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This includes 
\emph on
all
\emph default
 fiscal externalities from all behavioral responses to the policy.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define the 
\series bold
Marginal Value of Public Funds (MVPF) 
\series default
of policy 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MVPF_{p}=\frac{\int_{i}WTP_{i}}{G}=\frac{\text{Willingness to Pay}}{\text{Net Cost}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thought experiment: $1 of government spending on the policy delivers 
\begin_inset Formula $\$MVPF$
\end_inset

 of benefits to the policy's beneficiaries.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
And $1 of spending delivers 
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{green}\bar{\eta}_{p}}MVPF_{p}$
\end_inset

 in social welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
recall 
\begin_inset Formula ${\color{green}\bar{\eta}_{p}}=\int{\color{green}\eta_{i}}\frac{WTP_{i}}{\int_{i}WTP_{i}}$
\end_inset

 captures the distributional concerns: It's the incidence-weighted marginal
 social welfare weights.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
With the MVPF we can try and construct portfolios of policy reforms that
 increase welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take two (non budget-neutral) policies: policy 1 and policy 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Combine into a budget-neutral policy 
\begin_inset Formula $dp$
\end_inset

 that increases spending on policy 1 financed by decreasing spending on
 policy 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To first order, this is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

good
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 idea 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(dW/dp>0\right)$
\end_inset

 if and only if
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\eta}_{p}MVPF_{p}>0\iff\bar{\eta}_{1}MVPF_{1}-\bar{\eta}_{2}MVPF_{2}>0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The MVPF normalizes the net government spending on the two policies so we
 can compare them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note that a lot of 
\emph on
normative
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

should
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) judgements are embeded in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\eta}$
\end_inset

s.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 more straightforward to make comparisons between policies that have similar
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\eta}$
\end_inset

s.
 i.e.
 policies that have similar sets of beneficiaries.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An example: What is the MVPF of a (small) reduction in the marginal income
 tax rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the marginal tax rate on earnings 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (linear tax schedule for simplicity, but generalizes easily)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Average earnings in the population are 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsf{E}\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start with the denominator: Government revenue is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\tau\textsf{E}\left[y\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So a small tax cut has a marginal effect on government revenue of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{d\tau}=\frac{dR}{d\tau}=\textsf{E}\left[y\right]+\tau\frac{d\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{d\tau}=\textsf{E}\left[y\right]\left(1+\varepsilon\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon\equiv\frac{\tau}{\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}\frac{\partial\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{\partial\tau}$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of the tax base wrt the tax rate
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Note 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 captures the 
\emph on
causal
\emph default
 effect of the tax change on tax revenue.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now turn to the numerator: WTP.
 Here is where envelope theorem is powerful
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To first order, individuals don't value changes in their incomes (by EVT,
 since income chosen optimally)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So if you earn $100 and taxes go from 25% to 24% you lose $1 and your WTP
 to avoid that is $1, regardless of how you change earnings (what about
 evasion?).
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{d\tau}\frac{v_{i}}{\lambda_{i}}=y_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So, the average WTP for the change 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\textsf{E}\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

 and the MVPF is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MVPF_{d\tau}=\frac{\text{WTP}_{d\tau}}{G_{d\tau}}=\frac{\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{\textsf{E}\left[y\right]\left(1+\varepsilon\right)}=\frac{1}{1+\varepsilon}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
So the key thing we need to know is the causal effect of changing tax rates
 on government revenue.
 For every $1 of a tax cut, by how much do individuals change their incomes
 (and all other taxable behavior).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At home: Try thinking about how these expressions change if the tax cut
 is only for high earners above a threshold 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren (2016) Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Extreme cases of the MVPF:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
What happens if 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon<-1$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
the policy now 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

pays for itself
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: cutting taxes by $1 increased income by more than $1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This is the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Laffer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect, we were beyond the Laffer rate.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Define 
\begin_inset Formula $MVPF=\infty$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $WTP>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G<0$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $MVPF=-\infty$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $WTP<0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G>0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Policies with 
\begin_inset Formula $MVPF=\infty$
\end_inset

 pay for themselves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $MVPF=\infty$
\end_inset

 generalizes the Laffer idea that it is possible for a tax cut to pay for
 itself to other government policies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Surprisingly many examples of 
\begin_inset Formula $MVPF=\infty$
\end_inset

 despite very few of them being taxes!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
