\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What about other ways of doing welfare comparisons?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Another (historically) popular approach is to calculate the Marginal Excess
 Burden (MEB) of each policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
2 ways you can think of the thought experiment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How much extra revenue could the government get if the policy change is
 implemented but utility is held constant by using individual specific lump-sum
 transfers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
How much are individuals willing to pay for the policy if the government
 closes the budget constraint through taxes using individual-specific, non-disto
rtionary transfers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How different is this from the MVPF? It's all in the budget constraint!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Individuals face budget constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $c\leq\left(1-\tau\right)y+t$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is lump sum transfer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a policy reform 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau^{c}$
\end_inset

 that raises taxes by 
\begin_inset Formula $d\tau$
\end_inset

 and rebates lump sum 
\begin_inset Formula $dt$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
G_{d\tau^{c}}=\frac{dR}{d\tau^{c}} & =\underbrace{\textsf{E}\left[y\right]+\tau\frac{d\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{d\tau}}_{\text{tax rate cut}}-\underbrace{\textsf{E}\left[y\right]-\tau\frac{d\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{dt}}_{\text{lump-sum}}\\
 & =\tau\left(\underbrace{\frac{d\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{d\tau}}_{\text{inc + subs eff.}}-\underbrace{\frac{d\textsf{E}\left[y\right]}{dt}}_{\text{inc eff only}}\right)\\
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Normalize by WTP (
\begin_inset Formula $\textsf{E}\left[y\right]$
\end_inset

) and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MEB=\varepsilon^{c}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon^{c}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
compensated
\series default
 elasticity of tax revenue (only the substitution effect)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Two things make using the MEB hard:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Need the 
\emph on
compensated
\emph default
 elasticities.
 But typically the causal estimates that we have are of 
\emph on
uncompensated
\emph default
 effects.
 So we would need to estimate income effects (hard!)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Individual-specific transfers are not really feasible, that's how we got
 the whole field of optimal taxation!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nevertheless, if you can define and estimate the right quantities, you can
 compare the MEB across policies.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Another common approach is to estimate Benefit Cost Ratios (BCRs).
 Heckman et al 2010, much of regulatory policy.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Compare the net benefits to the program cost:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
BCR=\frac{\text{Social Benefits}-\text{Social Costs}}{\text{Program Costs}\left(1+\phi^{DWL}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiply the cost in the denominator to account for excess burden of taxation
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Revenue effects appear in the numerator
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hendren & Sprung-Keyser (2020)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/HendrenSprungkeyser_24.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 95page%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Sufficient Statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Chetty (ARE 2009) 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
protect
\backslash
textit{
\end_layout

\end_inset

Sufficient Statistics as Bridge
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): 2 Competing Paradigms
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
We can characterize 2 competing paradigms for policy evaluation & welfare
 analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Structural: 
\series default
specify a 
\emph on
complete
\emph default
 model, and estimate or calibrate the model's primitives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Reduced form:
\series default
 prioritize clean 
\emph on
identification
\emph default
 of causal effects.
 Accept narrower scope of analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
PRO structural / CON reduced form:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimate statistics that are policy-invariant parameters of models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Can simulate effects of changes in policies on behavior and welfare.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
PRO reduced form / CON of structural approach:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
(quasi-)experimental research designs achieve compelling estimates of treatment
 effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Need to estimate all primitive parameters.
 Impossible to be compelling (selection, simultaneity, omitted variables
 etc)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): A Bridge Between the 2
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Public Economics has pioneered an approach to compromise between the two:
 
\series bold
Sufficient Statistics
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Setup:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Policy instrument 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Social welfare 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{h}\gamma_{h}V_{h}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{What is }\frac{dW\text{\left(t\right)}}{dt}\text{??}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Structural approach: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Write model with primitives 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}=\left(\omega_{1},\ldots,\omega_{N}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Derive 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=f\left(\boldsymbol{\omega}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $dW\left(t\right)/dt$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): A Bridge Between the 2
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pictures/Chetty2009_1.png
	lyxscale 50
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Benefits
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Simpler to estimate.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Less data and variation needed to identify marginal treatment effects than
 full structural model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Especially beneficial with heterogeneity and discrete choice (lots of primitives
, still few MTEs)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Weaker assumptions and design-based empirical methods.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
more transparent and empirically credible estimates.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Can be implemented even when we're uncertain about what the right model
 is.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Chetty (2009): Costs
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Each question requires its own sufficient-statistics formula
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
e.g.
 unemployment benefit level vs duration of unemployment benefits; tax rate
 vs tax base etc.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In some settings it might be hard to characterize the sufficient statistics
 formula.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
More potential to be misapplied: A little bit of knowledge is a dangerous
 thing!
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
One can draw policy conclusions from a sufficient-statistics formula without
 evaluating the validity of the model it is based on.
 Structural requires full estimation of the model so can only draw conclusions
 from models that fit the data.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Remember Harberger's deadweight loss triangle? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
That's the first sufficient statistics formula! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sufficient statistic is the elasticity of equilibrium quantity of the
 taxed good wrt its after-tax price
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The structural primitives are the demand- and the supply-elasticities of
 all the goods in the economy
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a static, general equilibrium model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
An individual is endowed with 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 units of numeraire good 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (think of it as labor)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Firms use the numeraire as input to production of 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 consumption goods 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{J}\right)$
\end_inset

 with convex cost functions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j}\left(x_{j}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Total cost of production is 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\sum_{j=1}^{J}c_{j}\left(x_{j}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Production is perfectly competitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Government taxes good 1 at rate 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{p}=\left(p_{1},\ldots,p_{J}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the vector of (endogenous) pretax prices
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consumer takes prices as given and maximizes quasi-linear utility:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & \max_{\boldsymbol{x},y}u\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{J}\right)+y\\
 & \text{s.t. }\boldsymbol{p}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}+tx_{1}+y=Z
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Firms take prices as given and solve
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{\boldsymbol{x}}\boldsymbol{p}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These two problems give us demand and supply of the 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 goods: 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{D}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{S}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Markets clear to close the model: 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}^{D}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)=\boldsymbol{x}^{S}\left(\boldsymbol{p}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
What is the welfare cost of the tax 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

? It's the loss of social surplus from transactions that fail to take place
 because of the tax.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Conceptual experiment: what is the loss in welfare if we raise the tax rate
 and rebate the revenues lump sum to consumers?
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W\left(t\right) & =\underbrace{\left\{ \max_{\boldsymbol{x}}u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)+Z-tx_{1}-\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{x}\right\} }_{\text{consumer surplus \ensuremath{CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}}}\\
 & \quad+\underbrace{\left\{ \max_{\boldsymbol{x}}\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right\} }_{\text{producer surplus }PS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}+\underbrace{tx_{1}}_{\text{tax revenue}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Note: consumers don't take account of change in size of rebate when choosing
 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

: It is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
fiscal externality
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So how can we estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $dW\left(t\right)/dt$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 good demand and supply system to get 
\begin_inset Formula $u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The problem is simultaneity: To get the slope of the demand and supply
 curves, we need 
\begin_inset Formula $2J$
\end_inset

 instruments!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Harberger's simpler approach: Exploit the power of the envelope theorem.
 Consumers and producers are choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}$
\end_inset

 optimally so we can ignore behavioral responses 
\begin_inset Formula $d\boldsymbol{x}/dt$
\end_inset

 in the curly brackets: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dCS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{dt}=\frac{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial\boldsymbol{x}}\frac{d\boldsymbol{x}}{dt}+\frac{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial t}
\]

\end_inset

(and similarly for producer surplus)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Let's demonstrate this for consumer surplus
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consumer's FOCs are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{\partial x_{1}}=p_{1}+t\quad\frac{\partial u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}=p_{j},\:j=2,\ldots,J
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Totally differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dCS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{dt} & =\underbrace{\sum_{j=1}^{J}\left(\frac{\partial u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}-p_{j}\right)\frac{\partial x_{j}}{\partial t}-t\frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial t}}_{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)/\partial\boldsymbol{x}\;\partial\boldsymbol{x}/\partial t}\underbrace{-\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-x_{1}}_{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)/\partial t}\\
 & =-\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-x_{1}=\frac{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial t}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Precedent: Harberger (1964)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Using the power of the envelope theorem we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt} & =\frac{dCS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{dt}+\frac{dPS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{dt}+\frac{dtx_{1}}{dt}\\
 & =\frac{\partial CS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial PS\left(\boldsymbol{x};t\right)}{\partial t}+\frac{dtx_{1}}{dt}\\
 & =\left(-\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}-x_{1}\right)+\left(\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{p}\left(t\right)}{\partial t}\cdot\boldsymbol{x}\right)+\left(x_{1}+t\frac{dx_{1}}{dt}\right)\\
 & =t\frac{dx_{1}\left(t\right)}{dt}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $dx_{1}\left(t\right)/dt$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
sufficient statistic
\series default
 for the welfare loss
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Taxes induce behavioral responses 
\begin_inset Formula $d\boldsymbol{x}/dt$
\end_inset

 but these have no first-order effects on welfare because households and
 firms are optimizing (envelope theorem)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Taxes induce changes in prices 
\begin_inset Formula $d\boldsymbol{p}/dt$
\end_inset

 but these have no first-order effects on welfare, they only redistribute
 surplus between producers and consumers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Here's a general cookbook (we'll focus on a single agent in a static model,
 but easy to generalize)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 1: Specify the structure of the model.
 What are the agent's choices and constraints? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\max_{x}U\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\quad s.t.\;G_{1}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right),\ldots,G_{M}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{x}=\left(x_{1},\ldots,x_{J}\right)$
\end_inset

 are choices, 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tax
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is transfer in units of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{J}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Solution to this problem defines welfare as a function of the policy instrument
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
W\left(t\right)=\max_{x}U\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)+\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}G_{m}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Step 2: Express 
\begin_inset Formula $dW\left(t\right)/dt$
\end_inset

 in terms of multipliers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\left\{ \frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial t}\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We know 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial T/\partial t$
\end_inset

 from the government budget constraint, and can calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial G_{m}/\partial T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial G_{m}/\partial t$
\end_inset

.
 The key unknowns are the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{m}$
\end_inset

s.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Step 3: Substitute Multipliers by marginal utilities.
 The agent's FOCs imply
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial u\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)}{\partial x_{j}}=-\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial x_{j}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This maps the 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

s to the marginal utilities.
 Let's make an assumption on the structure of the constraints:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial t} & =k_{t}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial x_{1}}\;\forall m=1,\ldots,M\\
\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial T} & =-k_{T}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)\frac{\partial G_{M}}{\partial x_{J}}\;\forall m=1,\ldots,M
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt} & =\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\left\{ \frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial t}\right\} \\
 & =\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\left\{ -k_{T}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)\frac{\partial G_{M}}{\partial x_{J}}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}+k_{t}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t,T\right)\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial x_{1}}\right\} \\
 & =-k_{T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\frac{\partial G_{M}}{\partial x_{J}}+k_{t}\sum_{m=1}^{M}\lambda_{m}\frac{\partial G_{m}}{\partial x_{1}}\\
 & =k_{T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}u^{\prime}\left(x_{J}\left(t\right)\right)-k_{t}u^{\prime}\left(x_{1}\left(t\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Step 4: Recover the marginal utilities from observed choices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sometimes we make assumptions about the marginal utilities (e.g.
 quasilinear utility in the Harberger example means that 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}\left(x_{J}\right)=1$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In general, try and use the fact that the marginal utilites are inputs into
 observed choices and then recover them from how choices change in response
 to price/policy changes.
 e.g.
 in Harberger example, 
\begin_inset Formula $u^{\prime}\left(x_{1}\right)=p_{1}+t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A General Cookbook
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Step 5: Empirical implementation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The work so far tells us which empirical objects we need to try and estimate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{e.g. }\frac{dW\left(t\right)}{dt}=f\left(\frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial t},\frac{\partial x_{1}}{\partial Z},t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Estimate these objects using policy/price changes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Step 6: Model evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Test predictions of the model that was needed to get the sufficient statistics
 model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Identify at least one set of structural parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

 that is consistent with the model
\end_layout

\end_deeper
